<TITLE> Digital fair displays govt e-service </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 5 (bdnews24.com) -- The Digital Innovation Fair 2010 now underway at the capital's Bangabandu Novo Theatre is displaying e-services provided by different ministries and government departments. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina inaugurated the fair Thursday, where she affirmed the government's commitment to ensure transparency and curb corruption in the administration with the use of Information and Communication Technology. The three-day fair houses 118 pavilions, mostly of ministries and government departments along with six private entities. The rural development ministry is showcasing how a pilot project, which aims to disburse loans through machine readable ID cards. An official of the ministry said that around 2.5 lakh people of 27 upazillas of Faridpur district will benefit from the project. The Election Commission's stall is displaying the electronic voting system, while the education ministry is showcasing its project of mobile device as a tool of education. Ashok Kumar Paul, an engineer of the ministry, said that the pilot project would start very soon in 300 schools. The ministry is also showing how the student's Optical Mark Recognition registration process works. Flood alerts through mobile phones is displayed by the food and disaster ministry and the Bangladesh Railway's stall is educating people about its newest ticketing system using mobile phones. Meanwhile, Bangladesh Police is showcasing how citizens can get services from them through online. The fair, co-organised by the ICT ministry and the UNDP-funded Access to Information Program under the prime minister's office, will be open for all from 10 am to 8 pm till Sunday. The fair will also hold at least seven seminars on the role of ICT in the development process.
